Let Ari,t be the activity of neuron or site i in area A at timepoint t, where A can be L4 or L2/3 in the mouse data and V1 or V4 in the monkey data. Neuronal activity from one area (e.g., mouse V1 L4 or monkey V1) was used to predict activity in the other area (e.g., mouse V1 L2/3 or monkey V4) using ridge regression (Figure 1E). The activity of each neuron i in area A2 was predicted from nA1 neurons in area A1 as follows:
(3)
A2r^i,t=∑j=1nA1wi,jA1rj,t+bi \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} { }_{A 2} \hat{r}_{i, t}=\sum_{j=1}^{n_{A 1}} w_{i, j A 1} r_{j, t}+b_{i} \tag{3} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}

One–vs–rest self-consistency (1-vs-rest r2). For each neuron/site i with T repeat trials, let r(t) ∈ ℝM be its activity vector from repetition t across all stimuli/timepoints (length M, defined below). The leave-one-out mean response over repetitions excluding t is
r―i(rest)=1T−1∑t′=1t′≠tTri(t′) \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \overline{\mathbf{r}}_{i}^{(r e s t)}=\frac{1}{T-1} \sum_{\substack{t^{\prime}=1 \\ t^{\prime} \neq t}}^{T} \mathbf{r}_{i}^{\left(t^{\prime}\right)}$$\end{document}
Throughout, the superscript (rest) means “all repetitions excluding repeat t”.

The one–vs–rest correlation for the held-out repetition t is
(7)
SCi(t)=corr(ri(t),r―i(rest )), \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} S C_{i}^{(t)}=\operatorname{corr}\left(\mathbf{r}_{i}^{(t)}, \overline{\mathbf{r}}_{i}^{(\text {rest })}\right), \tag{7} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}

We then average these correlations across all held-out repetitions:
(8)
SC―i=1T∑t=1TSCi(t). \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} \overline{S C}_{i}=\frac{1}{T} \sum_{t=1}^{T} S C_{i}^{(t)} . \tag{8} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}

Variance metrics. All variances were computed on gray–baseline–subtracted signals. In mice (32 gratings, K repeats), for neuron i, let r(k,s) denote the scalar response to stimulus s ∈ {1, …, S} on repeat k ∈ {1, …, K} (repeat-averaged within the analysis window). We defined:


r¯i(s)=1K∑k=1Kri(k,s)
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle \bar{r}_{i}^{(s)}=\frac{1}{K} \sum_{k=1}^{K} r_{i}^{(k, s)}$$\end{document}





vitrial =1S∑s=1SVark(ri(k,s))
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle \quad v_{i}^{\text {trial }}=\frac{1}{S} \sum_{s=1}^{S} \operatorname{Var}_{k}\left(r_{i}^{(k, s)}\right)$$\end{document}

In monkeys, for the checkerboard stimuli, for site i let r(k,t) denote the scalar response to time-point t ∈ {1, …, T } on repeat k ∈ {1, …, K}


r¯i(t)=1K∑k=1Kri(k,t)
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle \bar{r}_{i}^{(t)}=\frac{1}{K} \sum_{k=1}^{K} r_{i}^{(k, t)}$$\end{document}





viacross =1T∑t=1TVark(ri(k,s))
\begin{document}$$\displaystyle \quad v_{i}^{\text {across }}=\frac{1}{T} \sum_{t=1}^{T} \operatorname{Var}_{k}\left(r_{i}^{(k, s)}\right)$$\end{document}

In monkeys, for the moving bar stimuli, the same two metrics were computed per stimulus s and then averaged across the four stimuli. In addition, we defined an across-stimuli variance of the time-averaged, trial-mean response:
(13)
vistim =Vars(r¯i(s)), where r¯i(s)=1K∑k=1K(1T∑t=1Txi(k,s)(t)), \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} v_{i}^{\text {stim }}=\operatorname{Var}_{s}\left(\bar{r}_{i}^{(s)}\right), \quad \text { where } \bar{r}_{i}^{(s)}=\frac{1}{K} \sum_{k=1}^{K}\left(\frac{1}{T} \sum_{t=1}^{T} x_{i}^{(k, s)}(t)\right), \tag{13} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
